WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Okay, so welcome back everyone. This is our third talk on the maintainers track.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
We're excited to hear about user guides by Michael Chow.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.000
All right, thank you. Whoa, okay, so sorry, came in hot.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
All right, thank you so much. Hope everybody's enjoying SciPy.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I have to admit that I'm really excited to finish this talk so that I can enjoy SciPy.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
But I'm also really excited to give it.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Yeah, so I'll be talking about user guides and this idea of welcoming new users and delighting old ones.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
I also have to admit I didn't love the idea of calling some people old users.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
But so if you know a better word, I'm all ears.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Experienced users, we got it. So just a little bit of background on me.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.000
My name is Michael Chow. I did a PhD in cognitive psychology.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And I work on open source data tools at PositPBC, mostly on Python tools, for example.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:13.000
One tool I maintain is called Great Tables, and it's all about displaying tables for publication.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Aside from that, I have two beautiful cats, Bandit and Moondog.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.000
And I will say one is very sassy, one is a real goober, and I'll let you decide which is which.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Yeah, so I'm really excited about user guides. I think part of it is as a cognitive psychologist,

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
I'm really interested in how people pick up new skills.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:50.000
And as a software developer, I'm really interested in sort of my responsibility in dumping how people should use a tool

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:57.000
and being sure that people can use a tool to do the kind of range of things I hope that they can do with it.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
I think a lot of open source developers, we build tools because we think they give people

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
a new or a better way to approach a problem.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And I think user guides are really the bridge from our kind of like hope inside our brain

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.000
that people can solve problems in a new way to actually putting our tools to use.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And to motivate this talk, I just want to bring up a scenario.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So I work a bit on the documentation for Plot9, which is a Python plotting library.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And suppose that you saw this graphic and you wanted to reproduce it.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:40.000
I would say an interesting question is, how would you go about that?

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:46.000
On the one hand, you could crack open Plot9's API reference, and you might see something like this,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
which is a list of a bunch of functions you could use from Plot9.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
But this isn't even the whole story.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
If we zoom out a little bit, there's actually more functions.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And if we just keep zooming, there's actually like 40 of these.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
These are called geomes.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.000
But wait, there's more.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
If we keep going, actually what you're going to see is this.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Geomes are like this little piece of the API reference.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:18.000
But there are a lot of other kinds of things, like facets, scales, and positions.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Obviously, these went into the plot that you're trying to create.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
But this would be a really tough place, I think, to start.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:31.000
You would just be waiting around for a long time, super confused.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
But what if you saw a simple example instead?

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:41.000
So what if you saw a really simple plot that used some key pieces of Plot9?

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
For example, what if it used facet wrap to create subplots?

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:52.000
This helps sort of set up a sense for how Plot9 puts things together.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And it could mention that it's using geome smooth and geome point to actually put things on the plot.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
So geome smooth puts that blue line in each of these subplots.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And geome point puts the points there.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And we could point out that scale color continuous is what makes this color bar from, say, blue to yellow.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So I think this is really helpful because this is a sort of minimal example

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.000
that gives you a sense for how some of the pieces of Plot9 fit together.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.000
So you can navigate things like the API reference to do what you want.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
I also wonder what if you saw the big pieces.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:42.000
So rather than this API reference, squint your eyes, I mean, it's all there.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.000
What if you saw something like this?

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:52.000
This is, I think, like 16 pages that just summarize the big pieces of Plot9

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:57.000
and help you get a sense for how all of it fits together.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
I think these are really important jobs.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And I think these are essentially what a user guide does.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:11.000
So I would say a user guide is concrete and sort of right sized for getting into a tool.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
And user guides are all over.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
So you might know them by a lot of names.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
So in FastAPI, it's the learn button.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
In Pollers, it's just called user guide.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
We love that.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
In Plot9, it's guide.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
But all of these go to the same kind of thing.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:39.000
I also think really interestingly, if you click this probably most prominent button,

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
it usually takes you to the user guide.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.000
So user guides are really front and center in documentation.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:53.000
They're probably the most prominent call to action that documentation sites give.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:55.000
So it's really important to get it right.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:04.000
And my hope in this talk is to lay out the two key pieces to focus on for getting a user guide right.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
So the first one I'll talk about is onboarding.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:15.000
So, for example, we showed what I call like a simplest whole task with Plot9.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:21.000
What's the sort of simplest whole plot we could show someone that's exciting

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:29.000
but also easy to break apart so they can get started with the pieces.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And I'd say I'll go through some other examples to kind of like flesh out the onboarding story with FastAPI

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
and a resource called R for Data Science.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:49.000
But jumping to the second piece, I would say it's sort of like grazing.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And in this talk, I'll use a sidebar as an example for grazing.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.000
But once you get through the simplest whole task,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:03.000
how do you then sort of keep going through a library from beginning to end?

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And how do you do something that gets you through prerequisites

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:15.000
but then lets you come back as you take on different tasks to find the sort of big pieces you need?

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:20.000
And again, I'll hit on a FastAPI and R for Data Science example

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:28.000
to try to flesh out different focuses for sidebars and grazing

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:34.000
that I'll say is one's frontloading and the other I'll call backwards chaining.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.000
All right.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.000
So I'm going to start.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
I'm going to go down the line with Plot9, the FastAPI, the R for Data Science

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:48.000
to try to highlight key focuses for onboarding and grazing.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.000
All right.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So starting with Plot9, I really want to focus on this idea of this simplest whole task

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
and having a good hierarchy to your user guide.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:01.000
All right.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
So we looked already at this plot.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:07.000
I'm going to show the Plot9 overview page,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.000
so sort of the starting page of the user guide

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:15.000
and how it sort of carves up this simplest whole task.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
So to start, it shows you the plot that you'll be making

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
so you know sort of what you're getting into

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
and hopefully it's like something interesting to you

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:30.000
that actually shows off why you might use Plot9.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
I think this table of contents, this floating table of contents,

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:38.000
helps show some of the structure that there are, say, three

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
I need to stop pointing with my hand because I think

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
I don't know if people can see it everywhere,

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:50.000
but there are sort of like seven big categories that the overview will emphasize.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And interestingly, in Plot9, each category is sort of a grouping of functions

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
that starts with, is prefixed with the category.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So geom functions start with the word geom.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:05.000
OK.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
So basically, to give you a sense for the overview, what happens is

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
each of these categories is previewed quickly

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
and each of these is just a little bit of text.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
So a couple sentences followed by a little code

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.000
and then the output of the code.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:27.000
So people can see, they saw the original plot they'll be making

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
and then they can see it being built step by step.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
This is called a worked example.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
You're showing, you're sort of working through the process.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:39.000
You're not necessarily asking people to do things,

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
but you're working it out and you're pointing their attention

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
at things they should care about in these outputs.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:47.000
All right.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:52.000
So these are the sort of quick explanations in the initial overview

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
so people can see how these seven pieces fit together

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
and do different pieces of plot nine.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
The next thing I want to point out is that,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
so zooming out, this is the sidebar.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:10.000
So these are the sort of like chapters in the plot nine guide.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:14.000
And basically how it works is that the pieces that were talked about

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
in the overview are then,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
plot nine goes on to dive deeper into each one

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
in a subsequent page or chapter.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
So you can see this thing called AAS,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:30.000
this isn't short for aesthetic mapping,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
is then covered in detail.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And I'll call this a detail spiral.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:40.000
So basically the overview page covers in brief each of these things

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
and then a subsequent section, basics,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.000
goes into detail on each of these pieces in depth.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
This lets people get a broad sense for how to use your tool on a real task

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:57.000
before diving deeper into each piece.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
I think this also helps with prerequisites

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
because this means, you know,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
a lot of these pieces don't just work in isolation,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
they depend on each other a little bit.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
So by covering all of them,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:14.000
you get some of the prerequisites out of the way.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
And this is just showing the detail spiral in a different way.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:21.000
So this is diagramming where people go through these concepts.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
So in the overview they do a broad pass over everything

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:29.000
and then they loop back and you sort of hit each one.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So just a quick diagrammatic representation.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
For the sidebar I'd say the value is sort of going from

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
things that focus more on prerequisites,

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
things you need to know to get started,

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:44.000
to more grazeable,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
so things that you can sort of sample as you go.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
Once you get to about geometric objects,

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
after this chapter,

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
you can sort of like click around quite a bit.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:59.000
And so the hope is that the titles and these sections

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
make it easy for people to see

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
different sort of categories of things they might do

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:09.000
and quickly key into different activities.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:10.000
All right.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:11.000
And just to show you by contrast,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
so this is without the sections.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
It's actually, I find it pretty hard to read

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
without this breaking apart into sections.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
And I see this a lot in guides

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
where you just have like 20 things

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
and I find it incredibly overwhelming.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So just a little bit of structure I think

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
helps people navigate a user guide.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
It also puts names on activities

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
which makes it easier to talk about.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
All right.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
So just to summarize,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
plot nine for onboarding,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
we talked a little bit about using a simplest whole task

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:53.000
to get people onboarded and familiar with key concepts

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:58.000
and then structuring your sidebar or chapters

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
so they're easy to graze

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:05.000
and easy to see how things are grouped.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:06.000
All right.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
So next I'm gonna look quickly at FastAPI

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
which is a really interesting tool

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
I think with a really nice approach to user guides.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
So the way FastAPI works is

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.000
FastAPI is a tool for building,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:24.000
it's a web framework

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
so you can deploy web applications

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
like this one shown in the browser.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
The tricky thing is that for a web application

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
is often there's something in the middle.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
So usually the process is

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
you might write some FastAPI code

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
and then there's this middle piece called a web server

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.000
which is not necessarily FastAPI

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
and then you interact with it in the web browser.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:52.000
So there's actually a lot of context

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
in which you're interacting with different things.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
You might be in an IDE writing code.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:01.000
You might be using this something like,

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
actually I've never said this word out loud,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
GUnicorn, is that?

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.000
GUnicorn?

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
Well, I mean, one of those two is right

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:10.000
to serve it

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
and then you might pop open your web browser

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
to interact with it.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.000
So FastAPI has a hard problem

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
because you could be in three different contexts

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.000
when you're using FastAPI.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
The way they handle this

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
is that they give you a simplest whole task

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
which is essentially like doing this

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
as fast as possible.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
So they just hand you the code

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
and they say copy this into a file

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
and then they just give you this special command

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
FastAPI dev

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
which runs the web application.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
So essentially they try to lift you past these pieces

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
so that you can get into the web browser

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
as fast as possible.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And this is a real risk

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
that I see sometimes with these tools

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.000
is some tools instead will tell you

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
about the middle thing in depth

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
and how you can use it

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.000
or they're actually like,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
probably like five different web servers you can use

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
and some things take the chance

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
to kind of tell you about each one

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
but I think FastAPI does a good job

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
of just actually telling you about none of them

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
and getting you to the kind of end product.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.000
You'll have time later to learn about the middle part

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:27.000
but FastAPI wants you to know what it does well for you.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:31.000
So this is showing a bit of what FastAPI did there.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
So they gave you task support.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
They just handed you the code.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.000
They just handed you this special command

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
and they got you to pop open a web browser.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
That's actually a ton of work.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.000
I think that FastAPI got you super far

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
and I think if you're new to programming

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
or new to web applications

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:56.000
they got you through a ton of stuff really fast.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.000
I think the interesting thing is the next piece they do

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
is they start to work backwards.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
So rather than diving into the code

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
they say, well you've already got the web browser open

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:11.000
so why don't we just tell you about what we're giving you

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
and they explain special FastAPI features

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
like their automatic documentation.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
So I think this is really neat.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
They've basically lifted you to the end product

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
and they're explaining to you what it does.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
Then they loop back and explain the code in detail

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:32.000
after they've sort of gotten you to appreciate the end thing

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
and understand what an end goal looks like.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
The other interesting thing is their sidebar structure looks like this.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
This is a bit in the weeds

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:50.000
but they talk a lot about concepts

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
but rather than...

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
Plot 9 basically went in order like

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
this is thing A, this is thing B, this is thing C.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
FastAPI does an interesting thing

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:02.000
they automate through topics.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So they start with path parameters, query parameters, request body.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:09.000
These are kind of like the initial prerequisites

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
but then they start looping back

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
to things they think you'll want to use first.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
So they don't do all the path stuff in depth.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
They then loop back to querying.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:24.000
And I think the way that they maintain a sense of structure

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.000
about FastAPI is they front load all the titles.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:35.000
So notice that path starts chapters 2 and 6.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:38.000
Notice query starts 3, 5, and 7.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
They sort of use this to flag to you

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
hey, we're alternating through these things

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
but these are like the three big things we care about.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
Yeah, I added the colors so I cheated.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:54.000
My hope is like when you stare at it long enough

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
it starts to make sense.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
But yeah, I added it just so people could see it quick

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:02.000
because this is a talk and we don't have time

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
to really marinate in it.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.000
The other thing is they back load subtopics.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:12.000
So notice like these two chapters are about

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
these main topics and then validation.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
So they're sort of weaving it together

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:22.000
and I think they're really cleverly using front loading and back loading

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.000
to try to flag the structure to you.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
And because you asked that great question

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
here's the sidebar without coloring.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
Obviously as a cognitive psychologist

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
I want to acknowledge that I cheated

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
and I showed you colored things.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
So I've primed you to see it.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Coloring?

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
I think you should submit it.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
We'll figure it out.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.000
So this is without color.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And the thing I want to flag is that

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
without front loading like if you

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
were to kind of like put something before

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
the front loaded topics

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
I think that it could really

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
make it hard to see

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
the kind of key topics.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
So this is like

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
one of the challenges with giving titles.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
But I think that front loading here

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:16.000
really helps you see the structure of FastAPI.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
And without something to

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
distinguish

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
you could really run into the case

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
where everything starts to kind of run together.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.000
So Plot 9 used sections.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
FastAPI used front loading.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
But you want something to make it clear.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
All right.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
So we talked a little bit about

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
for onboarding FastAPI provides

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
code and command line support.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:47.000
For grazing it uses front loading

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
to try to emphasize its structure to you.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
Now we're going to look at R for Data Science.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.000
Which is a bit funny as a user guide.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:58.000
It's a book that's like hundreds of thousands of words.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
But I think it's a good example

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
of what is essentially a really large document.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
So

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
just for a little background

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
R for Data Science is a book about

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
using R for Data Science.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:16.000
And it centers on this diagram

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:20.000
of this data science workflow or life cycle.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.000
Where you start by importing

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:25.000
or reading some data like a CSV in.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:26.000
You tidy it up.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.000
Maybe you fix the column names

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
or you reshape it a bit

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
as part of the tidying process.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
You then engage this cycle of

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
transforming, visualizing, and modeling your data

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
so you can understand it.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.000
And when you come to something really nice

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.000
that you want to send your boss or journal

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
you then communicate it.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:47.000
So this is the cycle of understanding.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.000
And the book is really structured around

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
this life cycle.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:56.000
And here's the structure of the book.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
So this is the introduction.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
And this is the chapter organization.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:04.000
And the thing I really want to flag here is that

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:06.000
first it's got this whole game section

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.000
designed to teach you about the life cycle.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
And it starts with visualize.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
So it actually doesn't start you from the beginning.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
I think what's notable is that

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:21.000
it can't do like a single chapter overview.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:23.000
It needs to break this up because it's pretty big.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.000
And it starts with visualize.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.000
And I think the real reason is

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:30.000
visualization's really satisfying.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
And it's also pretty close to like

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:35.000
seeing an end product.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:38.000
And then notice it keeps going backwards.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
So then it goes back to transform.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
Back to tidying. Back to import.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.000
So this is its way of handling a really big job

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:50.000
by breaking it up and chaining backwards

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:52.000
from the most satisfying or

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:55.000
a very like kind of end goal piece

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:58.000
to the beginning piece.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
And then notice the later sections

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
actually follow this as well.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:08.000
So the first section after this whole game onboarding

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:11.000
is visualizing followed by transform.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.000
So it's going backwards again

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:17.000
to try to kind of optimize for joy, I think.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:20.000
Another interesting thing is that it

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:23.000
kind of peppers in these prerequisites.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:27.000
So these are often like coding knowledge you need

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.000
for the book.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:31.000
But it doesn't want to just front load

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:33.000
all the coding pieces because

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:35.000
you would hate your life and you wouldn't be learning

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:37.000
R for data science.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:42.000
It works them in right before the point that you need it.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:46.000
So this is the spiral shown another way.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
I think this is a really neat way

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:51.000
to tackle a really big problem

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:55.000
by carving it up and working backwards.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
And just to emphasize,

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
I think this is the door

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
because it's the most satisfying

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
and it's close to an end product.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:06.000
All right.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:09.000
So, yeah, we talked a little bit about onboarding.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:14.000
We talked about plot nine to use a simple whole task.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
Fast API to support people to the end goal.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
And R for data science to backwards chain

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.000
and teach the most satisfying thing.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:26.000
First, we also looked at grazing

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.000
where you break up your sidebar

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.000
to create an information hierarchy

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
so people can see the parts

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
and it doesn't all blend together.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:37.000
How you can also front load

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
to emphasize the structure.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.000
Or like R for data science,

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
if you have a really big job,

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:45.000
you can backwards chain

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.000
and start with the end thing

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:50.000
and work backwards.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:53.000
I think these are really important, powerful moves

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:56.000
because tools are complicated

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:00.000
and it's really hard to learn a new tool.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:04.000
And people need all the help they can get

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
both to get started

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
and to come back

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:11.000
as they need things to handle new tasks.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:14.000
So I think the more we can do to bring people in

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:15.000
but also provide a structure

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
that makes really clear

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:21.000
how our tool fits the way we want them to think,

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:25.000
the better people will be at using our docs

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:28.000
through the sort of whole life cycle

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
of the tasks they're trying to do.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.000
So thanks a lot for listening.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.000
And I'm sorry I was checking the time.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.000
I'm so excited for your questions.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:44.000
Applause

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
First question is from Kayla.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:48.000
What thoughts do you have on tools

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
to automatically generate doc strings

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:51.000
and documentation?

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:52.000
Good, bad?

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:53.000
Such a good question.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:56.000
Well, what if I told you I myself

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.000
was the maintainer of a tool

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
to generate API references?

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
I think that...

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.000
Okay, this is what I would say.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:07.000
I actually had this as a starting thing.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:10.000
So I maintain a tool to generate API references.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.000
Things like this.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
So like each of your classes,

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:14.000
each of your methods.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.000
And I would say like

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:19.000
people always ask me about the API reference

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
which makes sense because I maintain the tool to build it.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
But I always think about this.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:26.000
The tool itself,

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
actually I've spent more time on the user guide

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
than the API reference.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
Like I think that engineers

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
always go API reference first.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
Like I've never seen an engineer

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
not do API reference first.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
And my story is like

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
you should user guide first.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.000
Like you can write doc strings

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
but you should just pretend they don't exist

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:48.000
until you have a user guide.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
And that's what I like about FastAPI.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.000
They actually had a user guide

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
before an API reference.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:57.000
I just think it's a really good forcing function

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:00.000
for thinking about the story you want to tell

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:03.000
rather than how each individual piece works.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:05.000
But I think they're cool.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:07.000
I think they're obviously really important.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:08.000
Thanks.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:09.000
Peter asks,

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:12.000
do you see the role or format of user guides changing

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
when many people's new default way of learning about a package

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:17.000
will be to ask an AI chatbot about the package?

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:18.000
Yeah, it's a good question.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.000
I mean,

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:21.000
I don't...

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:22.000
It's such a good question.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:23.000
I have no idea.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:24.000
I think...

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:25.000
My guess though is that

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:26.000
there's so much low hanging fruit

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.000
in terms of writing user guides

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:30.000
and documentation in general

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:33.000
that we're not really at the point I think of...

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.000
There's so much on the table right now

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:38.000
that you could do, I think,

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
to improve user guides

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
that it's probably okay to assume that

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.000
your improvements to user guides

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
will also be picked up by AI

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:48.000
either as context

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.000
or as part of training.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
And I think also

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
it's a good way to just sharpen your thinking.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
Like a big piece of,

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:00.000
I think a user guide and documentation

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.000
is having a controlled vocabulary.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:04.000
So I think like having to work out

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
like what are the sections

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.000
is also a good way to ensure

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:12.000
that you're using sort of systematic language

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:13.000
and categories.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.000
And I suspect that

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:18.000
AI will heartily take advantage of that

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
because it will have like consistent words

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.000
and categories to use.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:26.000
So Charles asks,

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
is the spiral about trying to keep readers

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
in the zone of proximal development?

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:32.000
Yeah.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:33.000
Yeah, I think so.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.000
Like essentially...

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:36.000
Yeah, you're like

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:39.000
bringing down the difficulty by

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
kind of like building their skill

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:44.000
in the things they need.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:45.000
Yeah.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:47.000
Okay.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:48.000
Lauren was wondering,

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.000
is it useful to have a user guide

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:51.000
be part of a repo

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.000
to facilitate contributions

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:54.000
from the point of view of users

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:55.000
instead of authors?

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:56.000
Is that common?

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:57.000
Oh, like

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:01.000
you said user guide like in its own repo.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:03.000
Yes.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:04.000
What a great question.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
I actually have a user guide.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.000
So the plot nine guide,

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
I own the repo.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:12.000
So I don't know if this counts,

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:13.000
but

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:15.000
the reason I did this was

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:17.000
maybe for that reason,

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:18.000
as I said, like,

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:19.000
this is such a big job.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:20.000
This is basically like

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
as if you had like a dependency on plot nine

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:25.000
or you were like

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
a tool to explain plot nine,

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:29.000
like that.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
I just asked plot nine's author,

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:32.000
Hassan,

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:35.000
to just like delegate to me the job

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:36.000
of running the guide.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
And I don't know if that's the exact question,

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
but I think relatedly like

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:41.000
I was like,

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
I need to be fully immersed

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:44.000
in this task

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:45.000
because

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:47.000
it's

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
a job just as important as

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:52.000
writing the plot nine code.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:54.000
So I think that

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:55.000
yeah, I think

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:56.000
I think it's helpful

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
and it's an activity that should be

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.000
seen as just as big

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:02.000
and challenging.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:04.000
Yeah.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:05.000
Thanks.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:06.000
Max has a question.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:07.000
Aside from doc strings,

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:09.000
auto-generated API guides,

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
how do you ensure that docs are up-to-date

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:12.000
with the code

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.000
and a continuous integration cycle?

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:19.000
I feel like

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
when I see user guides

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:25.000
that could use sprucing up,

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:26.000
like I,

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:27.000
well, okay.

